# Q1 ‚Äî ARCHITECTURE ANSWER
## Why Native Power Fx Cannot Meet AC2‚ÄìAC4 (and What Must Replace It)

---

### The Root Problem ‚Äî Three Compounding Limitations

**Limitation 1: Power Fx has no fuzzy or phonetic functions.**
Every text function in Power Fx is exact:

| Function | Behavior |
|---|---|
| `StartsWith()` | Exact prefix match |
| `EndsWith()` | Exact suffix match |
| `Find()` | Exact substring match |
| `IsMatch()` | Exact regex pattern match |

There is no `Soundex()`, no Levenshtein distance, no phonetic encoder, no fuzzy operator of any kind. AC2, AC3, and AC4 are architecturally impossible in pure Power Fx.

**Limitation 2: Dataverse OData does not support fuzzy or phonetic operators.**
Even if Power Fx could express a fuzzy query, the Dataverse connector's `Filter()` delegation translates to OData `$filter`. OData has no `~fuzzy`, no `soundsLike`, no edit-distance predicate. The delegation chain breaks before the query even leaves the app.

**Limitation 3: Scale disqualifies all client-side workarounds.**
With a confirmed growth trajectory of 100,000+ records, pulling data down to the client and filtering locally is not acceptable ‚Äî it would exceed Power Apps collection limits (2,000 rows), saturate network bandwidth, and produce multi-second load times. Every filter operation must execute server-side.

---

### Recommendation ‚Äî The Correct Architecture

> **Power Apps ‚Üí Power Automate Instant Flow ‚Üí Dual-Path Server-Side Search**

This is the recommended approach for Power Platform enterprise systems requiring fuzzy and phonetic matching at scale. It uses infrastructure already available inside your Microsoft 365 / Power Platform tenant (Dataverse Search is included with Dataverse) and adds one lightweight pre-computation pattern for guaranteed Soundex compliance.

---

### How the Architecture Works ‚Äî Two Layers

---

#### Layer 1: Dataverse Search API ‚Äî Handles AC2 and AC3 (Fuzzy Matching)

**What it is:**
Dataverse has a built-in search engine exposed at:
```
POST [org]/api/data/v9.2/search
```
This endpoint is powered internally by **Azure Cognitive Search** (Microsoft manages the index, the infrastructure, and the sync). It is included at no additional cost in your Dataverse subscription.

**Why it solves AC2 and AC3:**
The Dataverse Search API accepts **Lucene query syntax**, which includes the `~` fuzzy operator:

```
"Jhon~1"          ‚Üí matches "John" (1 edit distance ‚Äî handles typos)
"Smyth~2"         ‚Üí matches "Smith" (2 edit distance ‚Äî handles spelling drift)
"Jhon~1 Smyth~1"  ‚Üí multi-field fuzzy ‚Äî handles AC3 directly
```

Edit distance (`~1` or `~2`) means the engine accepts strings that differ by up to 1 or 2 character insertions, deletions, substitutions, or transpositions (Damerau-Levenshtein). This precisely maps to AC2 ("minor variations, spelling differences, typos, formatting differences") and AC3 ("values across two or more fields, spelling errors, typing differences").

**Scale:** Azure Cognitive Search backing the Dataverse index handles millions of documents with sub-second response. 100,000+ Persons records is well within its operating range.

---

#### Layer 2: Pre-Computed Soundex Columns ‚Äî Handles AC4 (Phonetic Matching)

**Why Dataverse Search alone is not enough for AC4:**
The phonetic analyzer configuration of the internal Dataverse Search index is managed entirely by Microsoft ‚Äî it cannot be customised. There is no guarantee that it applies a Soundex or Metaphone encoder to specific columns. AC4 requires deterministic, guaranteed phonetic matching behaviour.

**The solution ‚Äî pre-compute and store Soundex at write time:**

| New Column | Table | Type | Example Value |
|---|---|---|---|
| `cw_SoundexFirstName` | Persons | Text (max 10) | `J500` (for "John", "Jhon", "Jon", "Johan") |
| `cw_SoundexLastName` | Persons | Text (max 10) | `S530` (for "Smith", "Smyth", "Smithe") |

A **separate maintenance Power Automate flow** fires every time a Person record is created or updated. It computes `SOUNDEX(FirstName)` and `SOUNDEX(LastName)` and writes the result back to the two new columns.

At search time, the search service flow computes `SOUNDEX(userInput)` and executes a standard Dataverse `List Rows` action with an exact filter on `cw_SoundexFirstName` and `cw_SoundexLastName`. Because these are plain text column exact matches, this query is **100% delegable to Dataverse** ‚Äî it scales to any record count with no Power Fx client-side processing.

**Why this approach is correct:**
- Soundex encoding is a bijective hash: the same name always produces the same code
- Matching encoded input against encoded stored value is an exact operation ‚Äî fully delegable
- Industry standard in demographic search systems (SSA, DMV, law enforcement identity resolution)
- No external services. No extra cost. Runs entirely within Power Platform

